Installation and Dataset

1.Installation

The name of linear regression Package is FinalProject7. The repo contains the orginal package files is AU-R-Programming/FinalProject7. It also can be downloaded and installed by

devtools::install_github("AU-R-Programming/FinalProject7")

2.Dataset

The dataset used in this project as a example is forestfires.csv. For testing functions of this package, we select 3 variables in this dataset. Set FFMC as Set DC, temp as covariates.

data1<- read.csv2(file = "/Users/jc/Desktop/End/R-programming/Data/forestfires.csv",sep = ",")
response <- as.numeric(data1$FFMC)
covariates <- cbind(as.numeric(data1$DC),as.numeric(data1$temp))

Data has to be transformed to a vector(response) and a matrix(covariates) for running these functions of this package

Functions Introduction

1.Confidence intervals:

There are two functions used to calculate confidence intervals for linear regression coefficients. The first one is confi_inter() by asymptotic approach. alpha(default = 0.05) is significance level between 0 and 1.The second function is confi_inter_bo() by Bootstraps approach. alpha is the same as confi_inter(). m(default = 200) is Number of bootstrap replicates.

library(FinalProject7)
confi_inter(response, covariates, alpha =  0.05)
##               0.025        0.975
## Beta.1 80.911016461 83.866529457
## Beta.2  0.001459109  0.005412412
## Beta.3  0.252960944  0.421850894
confi_inter_bo(response, covariates, alpha =  0.05, m =200)
##               0.025        0.975
## Beta.1 80.899679944 83.772957640
## Beta.2  0.001600499  0.005461263
## Beta.3  0.254516439  0.419194791

The examples show the estimated confidence(0.05) intervals for three coefficients by two methods. Beta 1 is the confidence interval of intercept, Beta 2 and 3 are the estimated confidence intervals of variables DC and temp.

2.Plots:

The plot function ln_plot() can draw four kinds of plots by using different TYPE(“RF”,“QQR”,“HR”,“all”)

  1. Residuals vs fitted-values
ln_plot(response, covariates,type ="RF")

  1. qq-plot of residuals
ln_plot(response, covariates,type ="QQR")

  1. Histogram (or density) of residuals
ln_plot(response, covariates,type ="HR")

  1. All three plots above
ln_plot(response, covariates,type ="all")

3.Mean Square Prediction Error (MSPE):

The MSPE is a measure of a predictor’s fit. This function is used to calculate MSPE as follow.

l_mspe(response, covariates)
## [1] 24.20274

22.2 is the mspe of the linear regression model.

4.F-test:

This function is used to conduct F-test as follow.

l_ftest(response, covariates)
## [[1]]
## [1] 65.94111
## 
## [[2]]
## [1] 3.221918e-26

In the output of R, the first value is F-Value(65.94) of the linear regreesion model. The second value (3.22e-26) is p-value for f-test. The outcome of f-test implies that these covariates (DC,temp) have a significant linear association with response(FFMC).
